title: brackets for mounting DC jacket or switch in MDF panel or housing

description.text:
These small mounting brackets allow easy mounting of a DC jacket or a switch into a case or housing made of MDF panel or similiar material (5mm or thicker)  
DC jackets or snap in switches can be easily mounted in cases made of 1..2mm sheet material, ie metal or resin. For the jacket you need to drill a 6mm bore and for the switch you need to make a 13x19mm cutout.  
However, mounting them into 5mm or thicker MDF, multiplex etc. doesn't work to well for the screw of the jacket (too short) or the snap-in connector.  
What is more, making the rectangular cutout can be tedious when working in MDF or multiplex material.  
I happen to have a 25mm diameter cutting tool. Using that tool and the printed brackets, the mounting has become easy.

If necessary, adjust the params in the scad files.  
The supplied stl files are for 25mm diameter bore in the case panel and for a 5.5/2.5mm jacket with 8mm bore and for a miniature switch with 13x19mm cutout dimensions.  
Print the required brackets.  
Drill a 25mm hole using a cutting tool (see last photo).  
Insert the brackets and secure them with 3mm screws.

(Winch is functional - the bucket raises and lowers.)

To run the thread through the center beam:
  • Tie it tightly to the center of the rod, then loop it around the end of the rod. (Waxed dental floss works well - very strong.)
  • Push the rod into the horizontal hole in the center beam.
  • Catch the thread through the little hole in the base of the center beam with a pair of sharp tweezers and pull it down through the hole.
  • Tie the other end to the bucket handle and attach the end caps to the rod.
    • Turning the winch will raise and lower the bucket as the thread winds up on the rod, inside the beam. Stripped twist-tie wire makes a nice handle for the bucket - it's easily bent into shape and doesn't break easily.

description.text: These are the printed parts needed to add auto bed leveling to the Reprap Wilson (or any machine using the direct drive extruder from that project). The design will work with either the original fan duct (Jhead hot end) or the larger one used with the e3d-lite6. Video of assembly and walk-through of the firmware changes can be found here: https://youtu.be/qsmwGBuHoBU You will also need a 9g servo, snap action limit switch, some M2 screws and nuts, and a few zip ties to keep it all tidy.

• Attach 70cm wires to both the endstop switch and the servo motor.
  • Attach the endstop switch to the arm and secure wires with mini zip tie
  • Attach the servo holder to the servo motor using the small white actuator that comes with the servo, and secure with the flat head screw (also should come with the servo)
  • Attach the servo to the larger plastic piece as shown. Secure with an M2x16mm screw and M2 nut. The wiring from the servo should be routed through the hole on the top of the servo mount.
  • Secure the wires from both the servo and the endstop switch to the servo mount using a second mini zip tie.
  • Remove the two M3x30mm screws from the hot end mount.
  • Remove the two M3 nuts that held the hot end mount screws.
  • Re-insert the M3x30mm screws through the body of the extruder, loosely attach the M3 nuts, and then press the servo mount down to engage. Tighten.
  • Attach the endstop switch to the Z-min connection on RAMPS.
  • Attach the servo wires to the servo-1 connection on RAMPS.
  • Make sure the servo power jumper is installed on RAMPS.
  • Re-flash Marlin with auto bed leveling compiled in.
    • additional details on setting up Marlin forthcoming

description.text:
Propellers are neat things that you can attach to motors. When they turn, they create a pressure difference on the front/back of the blade. The front has high pressure, and the back has low pressure. 
These are done in Sketchup using a technique that I am developing. Each blade is 120 degrees from the others. The profile is extruded up 1/16" and then the top edge is rotated on the center point. The new top edge is then extruded again 1/16" and rotated by the same number of degrees. There is a line through the center to help locate the rotation point. This line would also be useful for placing a hole to accomodate a motor or other post. 
This design would be good to print and then make a mold of so you could make lots of propellers for underwater robots or airplanes or similar. 
After printing a few versions, it appears that the props need to have a steeper angle for proper Makerbotting. This will reduce the overhang, but will likely also require a taller blade to get enough surface area on the blades. 
If the profile of the blade is 1/16th of an inch, it seems to print neater and faster with abs. The included g code is based on MK5 with automated build platform. Having the angle too steep also makes for a sloppy print with lots of loops and drips. The three holes will allow the prop to be bolted onto a laser cut acrylic motor adapter.

Print it out and see how well it works. 
You will need to make a center hub for attaching it to the rotational device of your choice.
This is a very new design and technique, so mess with it and share your results!

description.text:
I want to be able to keep the cage door open enough for a new puppy to enter and exit but to keep out an older boisterous dog.  
Hopefully this door stay will do the trick.  
The stl is suitable for the cage I have but the scad file is parametric and can be easily modified to produce stays that should fit any wire cage.  
If you edit the scad you could even use it as a cable or pipe clip!

The stl is suitable for a wire cage with 4.5mm bars and is approx 100mm long.  I was hoping to be able to move the clip up and down the door frame to vary the opening, but the wires along the door opening are a different size to the wires that frame the door and cage. I think I need to do some more work on this.  
Warning: The clip on one of my test prints snapped when fitting to the cage. I will make the clips in the stl slightly bigger and reupload shortly.  
Update: Newer version of the STL with thicker clip ends has been uploaded.  Clip ends still snap on the thicker version. I am trying with wider clip opening.  
Update: Even with a widened clip opening the clips still snap sometimes. I would try printing in ABS rather than PLA but my ABS printer is off line for the moment. I will update when I have tried it.  
If you need other sizes feel free to edit the scad file!

Uh oh, time to take out the trash. But who is going to do it? Nobody wants to carry that many pizza boxes and coffee cups out to the curb. Let iTASK fairly allocate the task.   
Based on a Russian Roller, the names of each intern is inscribed on a side. The device is thrown and whoever's name is facing up gets the task.

Customize the sides, probably best by importing the .stl of the name plates, and creating a primitive of similar size before putting on your own text. This Russian Roller was glued together but feel free to experiment with friction welding (http://www.makerzoo.co/3d-printing-friction-welding/ :: wear safety goggles!)

title: Parametric Jaw Coupling with optional spider

description.text:
This is a remix of modilion and zignig's jaw coupling as I wanted one without a spider and a hub for attaching to shafts with variable attachment options on either hub.
Any number of struts (=legs=teeth) can be selected rather than the 2 per hub of the parent designs.
If the coupling is created without a spider then the each hub is cut out so they mesh tightly.
The current four options for attaching the couplings are:-
1) A captured nut and bolt perpendicular to the attachment shaft (eg for a motor shaft)
2) An inline captured nut into which can be screwed the main shaft (eg a threaded rod). (I'll probably drill and pin them together, but you could also use a self-locking nut, or possibly glue them.
3) A perpendicular hole through the entire hub to allow a bolt to be passed through (good for tubes which would be crushed by 1.
4) A slit though the base to allow it to clamp directly onto the shaft. You can print the spider, but I'd probably make one out of Sugru/oogoo(http://www.instructables.com/id/How-To-Make-Your-Own-Sugru-Substitute/) as a rubbery compound will have better shock absorption properties. Hot glue has also been suggested which might be OK for use at room temperature. If you print the mold you can easily use it to make multiple spiders of any compound you like.

I suggest you print each component separately and don't use the STLs as the undersides are not all aligned on the z axis.
Skeinforge and slic3r produce manifold error messages, but still seem to slice it correctly, so I'm not attempting to figure out the fault - have better things to do. Feel free if it bothers you or causes problems... There's quite a few ideas and code I've borrowed from others:
phraust's - cute mold
lievenstandaert - no spider
miseryBot - clamp
joostn - attachment
zignig/modilion - original code

description.text:
The Modular Hood for my Cokin Seris P filter system had broken, so I designed a replacement.  
the last photo shows the original (broken) one and the printed replacement.  
Replacement clamps on support as original did, by slightly pressing the two flat sides of the hood, widening the other two sides slightly to allow them to slip over the support until the support's pins go into the hood's slots.  
This first design does not reproduce the original's ability to stack several hood pieces together to make a longer hood, as I never needed it. If I have the time, I might make a second version that allows stacking.
I suggest printing in PLA, with 0.2mm layers and support turned on to get nice and precise slots.
